{
  "answer": "**Yama Smṛti (slug: `unknown-yama-smrti-552f8d`) does not contain specific rules laid down by Yama for purification after contact with the dead.**[^1][^2]\n\nThe text focuses primarily on penances (*prāyaścitta*) for sins such as killing, improper intercourse, eating forbidden foods, apostasy, and interactions with outcastes or animals. General purification methods are mentioned, such as bathing upon contact with impure substances (*amedhya*), touching fire, and observing twilight rituals,[^3] but nothing explicitly addresses ritual impurity (*aśauca*) from corpses or the deceased. Other Smṛtis in the corpus, like Manu Smṛti, do cover corpse-related purification (e.g., touching a corpse requires purity after one day/night), but this topic is absent here.[^4]\n\n[^1]: *Yama Smṛti*, Chapter 1, [full chapter](/works/unknown-yama-smrti-552f8d/01/translation/).\n[^2]: *Yama Smṛti*, Chapter 2, [full chapter](/works/unknown-yama-smrti-552f8d/02/translation/).\n[^3]: *Yama Smṛti* 1.4A, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yama-smrti-552f8d/01/translation/#p-65c739).\n[^4]: *Manusmṛti* 5.63, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/#p-89d810).",
